Unstructured NYC 311 complaint text was transformed into structured, actionable categories using a two-step NLP approach.
A representative sample was used to clean and combine key text fields, generate semantic embeddings, and cluster similar complaints. These clusters were reviewed and consolidated into business-relevant categories such as heating, noise, parking, sanitation, and infrastructure.
The learned patterns were then applied to the full dataset using batch processing, assigning each record an issue category and producing an enriched dataset. A summary of category volume and share is provided in full_issue_category_counts.csv, which highlights the relative distribution of issue types across all records.
To validate the transformation, a stratified sample of the enriched dataset was generated. This preview, available in sample_issue_category_preview.csv, displays original complaint fields alongside the assigned category, demonstrating how similar issues are consistently grouped while preserving record-level detail.
This process converts raw text into a scalable, interpretable feature that supports analysis of complaint trends, service demand, and operational performance.



